==English==

===Etymology===
Latin [[aggravatus]], p.p. of [[aggravare]]. See [[Aggrieve]].

===Pronunciation===
IPA: [[WEAE]] /ˈæg.rə.vet/

===Verb===
{{en-verb|aggravat|ing}}

# To make worse, or more severe; to render less tolerable or less excusable; to make more offensive; to enhance; to intensify. ``To aggravate my woes.'' &mdash;Pope.
#: To aggravate the horrors of the scene. &mdash;Prescott.
#: The defense made by the prisoner's counsel did rather aggravate than extenuate his crime. &mdash;Addison.
# To give coloring to in description; to exaggerate; as, to aggravate circumstances. &mdash;Paley.
# To exasperate; to provoke; to irritate. ''(Colloq.)''
#: If both were to aggravate her parents, as my brother and sister do mine. &mdash;Richardson (Clarissa).

